WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:14.800
On the structure of the glider charts.

2
00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:17.800
As I said, when you look at one for the first time,

3
00:00:17.800 --> 00:00:19.800
and you're not used to dealing with such charts,

4
00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:21.800
it can almost feel a bit intimidating.

5
00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:23.800
At least, that's how it looked to me

6
00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:25.800
at the start, when I first sat down with one.

7
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:29.800
But if you look at how the chart is built up from the ground up,

8
00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:31.800
and at all the boxes drawn on it,

9
00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:34.800
and the wavy lines on the chart,

10
00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:36.800
then it's actually,

11
00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:38.800
well, not that complicated.

12
00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:40.800
Then you know in principle

13
00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:42.800
what the boxes and wavy lines mean.

14
00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:45.800
And after that it's just an awful lot of detail packed on top.

15
00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:47.800
And sometimes it's still tricky

16
00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:50.800
to figure out which wavy line belongs to which airspace.

17
00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:53.800
But that's mostly a visual challenge.

18
00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:55.800
So, to build an understanding of the charts,

19
00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:57.800
I'm going to try,

20
00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:58.800
to show you a bit

21
00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.800
and build the chart up from the ground.

22
00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:08.890
First of all,

23
00:01:08.890 --> 00:01:10.890
there are lines you know,

24
00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:13.890
the dividing lines between the Mittelland and the Jura,

25
00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:14.890
and the Alps.

26
00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:16.890
It actually runs

27
00:01:16.890 --> 00:01:18.890
right across Switzerland,

28
00:01:18.890 --> 00:01:20.890
roughly from Lake Geneva,

29
00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:21.890
near Montreux,

30
00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:23.890
it cuts across central Switzerland,

31
00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:25.890
all the way to us,

32
00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.890
into the eastern Alpine region,

33
00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:29.890
and from there on into Austria.

34
00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:31.890
And that's how Switzerland gets divided up.

35
00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:34.890
And there's simply a topographical reason behind it,

36
00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.890
namely that in the Jura and the Mittelland

37
00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:39.890
all the mountains are much lower,

38
00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:41.890
and in the Alps they're quite a bit higher.

39
00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:44.890
And so the airspaces are pushed up a bit higher there.

40
00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:46.890
And that has an impact

41
00:01:46.890 --> 00:01:50.240
on us as paraglider pilots.

42
00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:52.240
Now let me explain.

43
00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:53.240
As I said,

44
00:01:53.240 --> 00:01:54.240
in G and E

45
00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.240
we can fly any time,

46
00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:58.240
and in C and D

47
00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:00.370
we need a clearance.

48
00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:01.370
And G,

49
00:02:01.370 --> 00:02:03.370
we can simply picture it

50
00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:04.370
as the blue band,

51
00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:05.370
like a carpet,

52
00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:06.370
laid across the whole of Switzerland,

53
00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:09.370
sliding across the entire topographical chart.

54
00:02:09.370 --> 00:02:12.370
And that carpet is 600 m thick.

55
00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:15.400
And the transition,

56
00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:17.400
once you're above those 600 m,

57
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:19.400
you go into E.

58
00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:21.400
There we're still allowed to fly.

59
00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.400
It's just a different airspace,

60
00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:26.400
with different rules.

61
00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:27.400
But for us as paraglider pilots

62
00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:29.400
we can fly in both of them.

63
00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:31.400
Then it gets interesting for us,

64
00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:33.400
namely where the boundary is,

65
00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:35.400
where E ends

66
00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:36.400
and C takes over,

67
00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:38.400
and we're no longer allowed to climb further,

68
00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.400
even in super thermals.

69
00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:41.400
At some point we have to say,

70
00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:43.400
okay, even though there's still a strong climb,

71
00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:45.400
we'd still rise further.

72
00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:47.400
The cloud base might be higher up,

73
00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:49.400
but we have to step out of the lift.

74
00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:51.400
And make sure we don't enter C.

75
00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:53.400
And that's where it gets really crucial,

76
00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:54.400
and also really important,

77
00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.420
that you know where the boundary is.

78
00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:58.420
In the Jura,

79
00:02:58.420 --> 00:02:59.420
so everything

80
00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:01.420
to the left of the dividing line,

81
00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:04.490
the boundary is at 3050 m.

82
00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:05.490
In the Alps

83
00:03:05.490 --> 00:03:08.490
the boundary is at 4550 m.

84
00:03:08.490 --> 00:03:10.490
So you can already see there's quite a difference

85
00:03:10.490 --> 00:03:11.490
in altitude,

86
00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.490
and of course also in the opportunities

87
00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:15.490
we have with the paraglider.

88
00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:17.490
Something very important to know,

89
00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:19.490
exactly,

90
00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:22.490
if a mountain there happens to be 4200 m high,

91
00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:25.490
you're still allowed to fly 600 m above it.

92
00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:30.490
So in that case you can actually fly up to 4800 m.

93
00:03:30.490 --> 00:03:32.490
And yes,

94
00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:34.490
clearly above the 4550.

95
00:03:34.490 --> 00:03:36.490
The condition is simply,

96
00:03:36.490 --> 00:04:03.020
well, yes,

97
00:04:03.020 --> 00:04:06.020
1050 m past that boundary, only this one time.

98
00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:08.020
up to 3950 m.

99
00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:11.020
Below that we still have the military hours.

100
00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:16.020
Those are also on the glider chart, and very important.

101
00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:20.020
It's always Monday through Friday, from 07:30 until 12:05.

102
00:04:20.020 --> 00:04:23.020
And from 13:15 until 17:15.

103
00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:27.020
The five minutes are simply to exclude any overlap.

104
00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:31.300
So that there's definitely no collision or incident.

105
00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:34.300
So very important, when the military is active,

106
00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:38.300
the boundary in the Alps drops a bit lower.

107
00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:42.300
But it's still clearly higher than in the Jura and the Mittelland.

108
00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:44.300
So just to recap quickly,

109
00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:50.300
the transition from E to C in the Mittelland is at 3050.

110
00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:55.300
In the Alps it varies depending on military activity.

111
00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:02.100
One small point,

112
00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:04.100
I forgot it earlier with all the airspaces,

113
00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.100
is airspace D, which is also controlled

114
00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:10.100
and where you may also need a clearance and radio contact.

115
00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:14.100
That comes into play above all near airfields.

116
00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:15.100
So we have G.

117
00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:17.100
The carpet that goes over the topography,

118
00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:19.100
above that E, and 3050.

119
00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:23.100
And D comes in mainly around airfields.

120
00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:29.420
All these airspaces are marked with so-called text labels.

121
00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:33.420
Here we see on the left the theory and on the right,

122
00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:35.420
what it looks like on the chart.

123
00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:39.420
The labels always show a lower limit and an upper limit.

124
00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:42.740
And here it's very important

125
00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:47.740
to know the difference between upright numbers and italic numbers.

126
00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:49.740
If it's upright, it's above ground.

127
00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:51.740
If it's italic, it's above sea level.

128
00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:54.740
And the second big difference

129
00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:56.740
I've noticed with the numbers

130
00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.740
is that the upper-limit numbers are blue and italic.

131
00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.740
Italic numbers also mean

132
00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:06.740
the altitude is in standard atmosphere.

133
00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:10.740
Now we see how in paragliding

134
00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:12.740
or in paragliding theory,

135
00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:14.740
all topics are always interrelated

136
00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:16.740
and somehow connected to another grip.

137
00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:20.740
In meteorology you've already heard a lot about standard atmosphere.

138
00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:23.740
Now it's exactly the same idea,

139
00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:26.740
namely that a standard pressure is also used here.

140
00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:30.740
And so the white numbers

141
00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:32.740
are the actual altitude,

142
00:06:32.740 --> 00:06:35.740
so if you use the GPS measurement for example,

143
00:06:35.740 --> 00:06:38.740
or something on the mountains or measured by altitude,

144
00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:41.740
so really the actual altitude on the gauge.

145
00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:44.740
And the blue italic numbers,

146
00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:47.740
those are numbers that fluctuate with the weather,

147
00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:51.740
because they're simply pressure-based,

148
00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:52.740
at sea level.

149
00:06:52.740 --> 00:06:54.740
And always assume

150
00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:57.740
that at sea level the same pressure is used,

151
00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:00.740
namely 1013.25 hectopascals.

152
00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:03.900
And why exactly that is,

153
00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.900
we'll try in the next few slides

154
00:07:06.900 --> 00:07:09.160
to bring across a bit.

155
00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:12.160
The altitude that we measure

156
00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:15.160
is done via a pressure measurement.

157
00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:16.160
That means

158
00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:20.510
any device measures a certain pressure,

159
00:07:20.510 --> 00:07:23.510
except for altitude measurement with GPS,

160
00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:24.510
but also,

161
00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:25.510
but also,

162
00:07:25.510 --> 00:07:26.510
the ground,

163
00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:27.510
also,

164
00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:30.510
(unclear),

165
00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:31.510
is the quarter.

166
00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:34.510
And with the stove and with the device specified.

167
00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:37.510
We can also suggest the millibar.

168
00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:39.010
That means

169
00:07:39.010 --> 00:07:40.510
also,

170
00:07:40.510 --> 00:07:41.510
the devices,

171
00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:44.510
(unclear),

172
00:07:44.510 --> 00:07:45.510
(unclear),

173
00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:46.510
(unclear),

174
00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:47.510
(unclear),

175
00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:48.510
(unclear),

176
00:07:48.510 --> 00:07:49.510
(unclear),

177
00:07:49.510 --> 00:07:51.510
(unclear),

178
00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:52.510
the meme of the stiff,

179
00:07:52.510 --> 00:07:59.070
During the day the pressure can shift too, and by the evening after landing

180
00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:02.790
your altimeter can already be off by a few metres.

181
00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:12.360
And to deal with that, a solution was found, and that solution is called

182
00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:17.920
flight levels — flight surfaces — and it comes from international aviation,

183
00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:23.480
because aircraft that fly from one airport to another, over long distances,

184
00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.800
fly through different weather zones and different pressure regions.

185
00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:33.360
And that means you'd actually have to recalibrate the altimeter every few metres, right?

186
00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:40.760
Yes, every few kilometres of flight you'd have to recalibrate, reset the ground pressure.

187
00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:45.080
You'd have to keep radioing in: what's the weather, what's the pressure on the ground,

188
00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:49.880
so that the altitude is correct. And that would be almost impossible and extremely time-consuming.

189
00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:55.160
And it would also carry the risk of running the same calculation errors,

190
00:08:55.160 --> 00:09:01.180
or that pressure shifts get mixed up and lead to discrepancies.

191
00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:08.570
So in aviation it was agreed that you don't fly by actual

192
00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:12.230
altitude, but by standard pressure.

193
00:09:12.230 --> 00:09:18.190
Standard pressure, as I said, 1013.25 hectopascals at sea level.

194
00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:25.190
And now here's a quick calculation example, before we get into flight levels.

195
00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:31.710
And how it works in practice, just so we get an idea of what it means.

196
00:09:31.710 --> 00:09:37.930
So the example with Flight Level 100, a flight level is 100 feet.

197
00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:46.410
That means Flight Level 100 is 10,000 feet, and because 1 foot is 30.48 centimetres tall,

198
00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:50.210
Flight Level 100 is then 3000 metres and 48 centimetres.

199
00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:53.250
And now you can see the connection.

200
00:09:53.250 --> 00:10:00.570
Or yes, we can explain why for example in the Jura, the level or the airspace

201
00:10:00.570 --> 00:10:03.090
starts at 3050 metres.

202
00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:08.090
That's actually Flight Level 100, and it comes from airline aviation.

203
00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:14.410
And in the same way, in the Alps the 3050 metres is Flight Level 100, and the 4550

204
00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:21.220
is Flight Level 150.

205
00:10:21.220 --> 00:10:27.950
And down low it's of course important that an aircraft flies at the exact altitude,

206
00:10:27.950 --> 00:10:33.550
simply because of the topography, so there's no collision with mountains or obstacles.

207
00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:42.470
But at a certain altitude it doesn't really matter so much, since the aircraft pass each other or run alongside.

208
00:10:42.470 --> 00:10:48.910
The most important thing is just that the aircraft are separated and not flying at the same altitude.

209
00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:54.870
And that's exactly what was achieved with the flight level — the goal was reached.

210
00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:59.590
As we see, if an aircraft flies from a high-pressure region into a low,

211
00:10:59.590 --> 00:11:04.070
it doesn't have to be such an extreme curve, of course; here it's shown a bit exaggerated.

212
00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:06.950
But then the flight level shifts a little.

213
00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:10.910
So the aircraft swims along a bit, dropping slightly here and there.

214
00:11:10.910 --> 00:11:15.110
But it's always at the same pressure, so the aircraft is exactly on the same pressure surface.

215
00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:21.330
And then it doesn't really matter whether it's at 11,000 or at 10,900,

216
00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:28.510
what's important is that aircraft fly at different levels so collisions can be avoided.

217
00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:36.990
Also on the glider chart, this is mainly the case with the TMAs and the Airways.

218
00:11:37.070 --> 00:11:42.230
We'll come back to those later, but if you look at the labels here,

219
00:11:42.230 --> 00:11:46.230
with airspace D, they always have a lower limit.

220
00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:48.310
Here it's the ground.

221
00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:51.990
Here we also have lower limits of 2500 and 2600.

222
00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:53.190
And those are fixed.

223
00:11:53.190 --> 00:11:56.430
It's very important that they're fixed, because of the topography.

224
00:11:56.430 --> 00:12:02.420
This is the example of Meiringen, which has very high mountains to the left and right.

225
00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:06.100
The upper limit, the 5300, that's where we're back in the range

226
00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:09.900
where it doesn't really matter, because there are no more obstacles.

227
00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:13.020
That altitude can fluctuate.

228
00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:17.620
And that's explained on this slide as well.

229
00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:22.180
So we have the topography, the lower limit is very strict,

230
00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:26.100
because if the pressure fluctuated there, we'd have problems.

231
00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:31.900
Then an aircraft could cut through, right into the mountain.

232
00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:36.460
It could run into the topography and cause a collision.

233
00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:40.050
The upper limit, though, that can fluctuate.

234
00:12:40.050 --> 00:12:42.610
And how much it varies, you can see here.

235
00:12:42.610 --> 00:12:46.330
This is also interesting to know when we're flying with the glider.

236
00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:49.930
By the way, the cells are shown on the glider chart.

237
00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:54.170
So, you see, at 1037 hectopascals.

238
00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:55.050
Ground pressure.

239
00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:58.810
And that's already, well, calculated as ground pressure.

240
00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:02.290
That's of course very high pressure.

241
00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:05.370
And there it makes about 200 m difference.

242
00:13:05.370 --> 00:13:10.730
Whereas in very low pressure, it's about minus 200 m.

243
00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:16.440
So it's actually quite a lot, though it should be said

244
00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.320
that in such low pressure we probably won't be flying.

245
00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:23.840
Normally, because the weather is just very bad and storms are coming in.

246
00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:26.640
In an extremely high pressure situation,

247
00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:30.200
we might do a soaring flight from a high alp into the mountain.

248
00:13:30.200 --> 00:13:33.800
But probably less of a thermal flight, because the air is just too stable.

249
00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:37.400
Now we're slipping back into meteorology a bit.

250
00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:41.920
But mostly we're in the range of maybe plus,

251
00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:46.280
perhaps even up to 100 m of difference when thermalling.

252
00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:50.160
And the good thing is that the deviation works in our favour.

253
00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:54.760
So when you know an airspace starts at 3050,

254
00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:59.880
and we're thermalling, it's usually a bit higher in practice.

255
00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:03.480
But it's still important that the device is set correctly

256
00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:07.070
and that you don't fly off based on a wrong reading.

257
00:14:07.070 --> 00:14:11.720
Now for a change, a sample exam question,

258
00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:15.720
which also comes up in the paragliding theory exam.

259
00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:21.960
We see here the upper limit of airspace class E over the Jura.

260
00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:26.960
Then we first have to think: how high would it be normally?

261
00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:31.760
In the Jura, we said, it doesn't matter whether the military is active or not,

262
00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:34.800
the upper limit for us is at 3050.

263
00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:37.120
Now we have a very strong high pressure.

264
00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:40.480
At first glance, you see lots of numbers and you get the feeling,

265
00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:43.480
oh wow, I have to do a precise calculation here and so on.

266
00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:48.200
But actually you're not expected to be able to do such a calculation.

267
00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:49.440
We've simply seen,

268
00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:52.280
since it's an incredibly strong high,

269
00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:57.120
in a very strong high it makes a maximum of about 200 m difference.

270
00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:00.520
And here we quickly see three, three, three or four E-options.

271
00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:02.160
Of course we have way too many.

272
00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:03.920
So it doesn't make that much difference,

273
00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:08.540
it always stays within a range of plus or minus 200 m.

274
00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:13.110
In case there's an exam question on it.

275
00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:17.110
Now we've made a small detour into flight levels.

276
00:15:17.110 --> 00:15:20.950
Yes, drifting a bit away from the glider chart.

277
00:15:20.950 --> 00:15:26.190
But also necessary for understanding how the airspaces are built up.

278
00:15:26.190 --> 00:15:28.030
I hope it helped a bit.

279
00:15:28.030 --> 00:15:31.350
Now we can come back to the other airspaces.

280
00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:34.910
Here are the airspaces D, which I mentioned briefly before.

281
00:15:34.910 --> 00:15:38.670
These are the so-called control zones,

282
00:15:38.670 --> 00:15:42.550
which are right in the immediate vicinity of the major airports.

283
00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:46.910
And they always go from the ground up to a certain altitude.

284
00:15:46.910 --> 00:15:50.310
Their shape is of course very topography-dependent

285
00:15:50.310 --> 00:15:54.340
and also depends on the approach corridors

286
00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:56.740
and on the needs of the airport.

287
00:15:56.740 --> 00:15:58.620
And they're of course not always round.

288
00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:01.260
Here it's just shown as a simple shape.

289
00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:11.220
D

290
00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:12.740
With the TMAs there's something special.

291
00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:15.180
So, for example, I have a sector,

292
00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:21.620
a TMA that runs into a mountain or into the topography.

293
00:16:21.620 --> 00:16:23.140
That happens sometimes.

294
00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:28.100
And here it's important to know that with the paraglider,

295
00:16:28.100 --> 00:16:33.380
but careful, only south of the dividing line with the Alps, so only in the Alps,

296
00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:37.100
you may fly 300 m below it.

297
00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:38.940
This applies in only a few cases.

298
00:16:39.020 --> 00:16:42.740
There's also an exam question that's a bit tricky,

299
00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:47.060
where you can fall in, so watch out with that 300 m rule.

300
00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:51.980
Of course there are launch sites where you, for example, take off here

301
00:16:51.980 --> 00:16:55.380
and fly out beautifully under those 300 m down below.

302
00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:58.580
And you're absolutely legal at all times,

303
00:16:58.580 --> 00:17:00.540
and don't need a clearance for it either.

304
00:17:00.540 --> 00:17:04.170
Then we have the airways.

305
00:17:04.170 --> 00:17:07.890
They connect the major airports

306
00:17:07.890 --> 00:17:12.890
and also the main routes of international air traffic.

307
00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:16.130
Here's a small view from Sion.

308
00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:22.410
We see, there are multiple TMAs — five, six, seven TMAs,

309
00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:24.890
or sometimes just one, it really varies.

310
00:17:24.890 --> 00:17:27.890
And as I said, it depends entirely on air traffic and the topography

311
00:17:27.890 --> 00:17:29.720
around the airport.

312
00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:35.780
The activity of the various TMAs differs too,

313
00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:41.060
if 9 is shown — so if the designation CTR, LSZR,

314
00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:44.300
if it says H24, then it's permanently active,

315
00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:46.860
like for example Zurich with the big airport.

316
00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:50.620
When it says HX, then there are no fixed operating hours.

317
00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:54.060
But you basically have to assume

318
00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:57.820
that it's active at any time, and you can check the status.

319
00:17:57.820 --> 00:18:00.020
And then there are the temporary ones.

320
00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:04.300
The temporary ones are announced via DABS

321
00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:07.260
when they're active.

322
00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:09.140
There are only two cases in Switzerland.

323
00:18:09.140 --> 00:18:12.820
Sion and Altenrhein, for example, we'll come back to that later.

324
00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:20.470
There are three activity statuses of TMAs and CTRs.

325
00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:25.490
We have quite a few heliports in Switzerland,

326
00:18:25.490 --> 00:18:29.330
they're marked like this, and we have to keep a radius

327
00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:32.210
of 2.5 km away from them.

328
00:18:32.970 --> 00:18:37.720
The smaller airfields without CTRs are marked like this.

329
00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:42.840
They have a radius of 5 km that we need to keep distance from.

330
00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:44.840
Here we have ten examples.

331
00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:48.840
There in the Lucerne area, that's a bit of a Bermuda triangle for us.

332
00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:51.240
We paraglider pilots, who we have to be quite careful,

333
00:18:51.240 --> 00:18:53.640
to make sure we never enter an airspace.

334
00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:55.440
But a really nice flying area.

335
00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:57.440
And we can definitely fly there.

336
00:18:57.440 --> 00:18:59.920
But it's currently very, very complex.

337
00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:02.920
Here you can also see all the examples

338
00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:03.920
that exist.

339
00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:06.920
There's a heliport with 2.5 km.

340
00:19:06.920 --> 00:19:09.920
The civilian airfields, then there are mixed airfields

341
00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:12.920
used for both military and civilian purposes.

342
00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:14.920
Then there are purely military airfields,

343
00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:18.210
marked in red and crossed.

344
00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:23.210
Interestingly, they only go up to 600 m above ground.

345
00:19:23.210 --> 00:19:27.210
We're allowed to fly over them above those 600 m.

346
00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:30.430
Or, well, without getting into trouble.

347
00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:34.800
On this topic it's also important,

348
00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:36.800
if you're on a cross-country flight,

349
00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:37.800
and you have the feeling,

350
00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:41.800
well, my ideal flight route and thermals

351
00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:43.800
and the glide angle and so on.

352
00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:46.800
My route goes right through there.

353
00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:48.800
Or we go just barely

354
00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:50.800
clipping a heliport.

355
00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:52.800
Then it's a sure thing,

356
00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:55.800
you should be in contact beforehand.

357
00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:59.800
And with the SHV, with the local clubs,

358
00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:01.800
they'll check whether at that heliport

359
00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.800
there's perhaps a local arrangement in place.

360
00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:05.800
If you don't have prior info,

361
00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:07.800
then you always have to assume.

362
00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:09.800
It's a 2.5 km radius

363
00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:12.800
and 5 km radius at airfields, and 600 m.

364
00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:15.800
Maybe, like in this case here,

365
00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:17.800
where it's cut into a specific shape,

366
00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:19.800
where there's a transit corridor through it.

367
00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:20.800
And you also see

368
00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:24.800
that ground goes up to 1200 m here.

369
00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:27.800
Above that it goes up to 800-900 m.

370
00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:30.800
That means it's clearly less than 600 m.

371
00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:33.800
And that can be very helpful,

372
00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:35.800
later in practice,

373
00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:38.800
if you just have this kind of information.

374
00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:44.660
Then on the glider chart, obstacles are also marked,

375
00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:46.660
looking roughly like this.

376
00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:50.230
Here, for example, the Säntis.

377
00:20:50.230 --> 00:20:54.230
We have the obstacle drawn at the top,

378
00:20:54.230 --> 00:20:56.230
and that it has a light,

379
00:20:56.230 --> 00:20:58.230
which is more relevant for aircraft

380
00:20:58.230 --> 00:20:59.230
that are out at night,

381
00:20:59.230 --> 00:21:02.230
the fact that it's lit is less interesting for us.

382
00:21:02.230 --> 00:21:04.230
What is interesting for us is,

383
00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:05.230
the heights shown,

384
00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:08.230
and here we get into italic script

385
00:21:08.230 --> 00:21:09.230
and upright script.

386
00:21:09.230 --> 00:21:11.230
Italic means above sea level,

387
00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:13.230
so that's the tip of the antenna,

388
00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:15.230
and the 124 m in upright script,

389
00:21:15.230 --> 00:21:18.230
that's how tall it is in real terms.

390
00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:19.230
So you know,

391
00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:21.230
okay, the antenna is this big,

392
00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:23.230
so you can see it from a distance and so on.

393
00:21:23.230 --> 00:21:25.230
Yes, that's just a reference point.

394
00:21:25.230 --> 00:21:27.230
Also important are the cables

395
00:21:27.230 --> 00:21:28.230
that are marked.

396
00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:31.230
With the 1264 m

397
00:21:31.230 --> 00:21:33.230
that's just the highest distance above the ground.

398
00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:35.230
So we can estimate

399
00:21:35.230 --> 00:21:37.230
how long the cable is.

400
00:21:37.230 --> 00:21:39.650
Very important,

401
00:21:39.650 --> 00:21:40.650
watch out,

402
00:21:40.650 --> 00:21:43.650
not every obstacle is on the glider chart.

403
00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:45.650
There are heaps of obstacles

404
00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:47.650
that aren't on it.

405
00:21:47.650 --> 00:21:50.650
For that you should also check the aviation obstacle charts,

406
00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:53.650
and even when you've checked them,

407
00:21:53.650 --> 00:21:55.650
fly with your eyes open.

408
00:21:55.650 --> 00:21:57.650
Don't just fly blindly into somewhere,

409
00:21:57.650 --> 00:21:59.650
because there can always be

410
00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:01.650
some piece of wood

411
00:22:01.650 --> 00:22:03.650
or a cable hanging somewhere,

412
00:22:03.650 --> 00:22:05.650
that, legally, doesn't have to be marked,

413
00:22:05.650 --> 00:22:06.650
doesn't need to be flagged,

414
00:22:06.650 --> 00:22:07.650
and which then,

415
00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:08.650
yeah,

416
00:22:08.650 --> 00:22:10.650
could become your undoing.

417
00:22:10.650 --> 00:22:12.650
So always fly with your eyes on,

418
00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:14.650
and also with the local pilots,

419
00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:16.650
and at the clubs and associations,

420
00:22:16.650 --> 00:22:18.650
and also at the stations

421
00:22:18.650 --> 00:22:19.650
of the cable cars,

422
00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:21.650
where you'll usually find very good info

423
00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:23.650
on aviation obstacles.

424
00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:24.650
On this topic,

425
00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:28.650
don't rely 100% on the glider chart alone.

426
00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:33.820
There are also quite a lot of these,

427
00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:36.860
the LSRs, the red ones,

428
00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:38.860
the red Rs, they're restricted.

429
00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:39.860
So they're a no-go,

430
00:22:39.860 --> 00:22:40.860
you can't fly there.

431
00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:42.860
On the glider charts

432
00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:43.860
the ones marked

433
00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:45.860
are those that are very often active,

434
00:22:45.860 --> 00:22:46.860
drawn in,

435
00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:48.860
and afterwards again

436
00:22:48.860 --> 00:22:49.860
we go into DABS,

437
00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:50.860
the evening before,

438
00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:51.860
to check,

439
00:22:51.860 --> 00:22:53.860
whether it's actually active,

440
00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:54.860
on the day,

441
00:22:54.860 --> 00:22:57.650
when I'm flying or not.

442
00:22:57.650 --> 00:22:58.650
Then there's

443
00:22:58.650 --> 00:22:59.650
LSD.

444
00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:00.650
That's not restricted.

445
00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:01.650
That's Danger.

446
00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:05.680
There you can basically

447
00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:06.680
fly.

448
00:23:06.680 --> 00:23:07.680
It's just not recommended,

449
00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:09.680
because dangerous things can happen there.

450
00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:10.680
We're talking about,

451
00:23:10.680 --> 00:23:11.680
for example,

452
00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:13.680
shooting on the ground,

453
00:23:13.680 --> 00:23:15.680
and that you'd be allowed to fly into a live-firing area

454
00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:16.680
in principle.

455
00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:18.680
It's of course not recommended,

456
00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:19.680
but in principle

457
00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:24.690
not legally forbidden.

458
00:23:24.690 --> 00:23:25.690
Here we have the example

459
00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:26.690
of an LSR,

460
00:23:26.690 --> 00:23:27.690
in our region,

461
00:23:27.690 --> 00:23:28.690
above Albstein,

462
00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:29.690
and in the Wäggital,

463
00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:31.690
the LSR three.

464
00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:32.690
And here,

465
00:23:32.690 --> 00:23:33.690
as you see again,

466
00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:35.170
a lower limit

467
00:23:35.170 --> 00:23:36.170
and upper limit.

468
00:23:36.170 --> 00:23:38.170
These are in red,

469
00:23:38.170 --> 00:23:39.170
italic.

470
00:23:39.170 --> 00:23:40.170
And that means,

471
00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:41.170
again,

472
00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:42.170
it's in standard atmosphere,

473
00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:43.170
and that the boundary

474
00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:45.170
of the military training area

475
00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:46.170
can fluctuate.

476
00:23:46.170 --> 00:23:47.170
fluctuate.

477
00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:48.170
It can be a bit higher,

478
00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:50.170
or a bit lower.

479
00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:53.280
Exactly,

480
00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:54.280
to show that a bit better,

481
00:23:54.280 --> 00:23:55.280
so you can see what's going on,

482
00:23:55.280 --> 00:24:01.280
a quick explanation of DABS,

483
00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:03.280
you'll find DABS

484
00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:06.280
at www.skybriefing.com.

485
00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:08.280
Right at the first step,

486
00:24:08.280 --> 00:24:09.280
very important,

487
00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:10.280
always check that the date is correct,

488
00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:12.280
because if you look at the wrong day

489
00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:13.280
by mistake,

490
00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:14.280
you might feel,

491
00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:15.280
everything's clear,

492
00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:17.280
I can fly anywhere.

493
00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:18.280
And on that day,

494
00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:19.280
when you're flying,

495
00:24:19.280 --> 00:24:20.280
some live-firing exercises are actually taking place,

496
00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:22.280
that's of course very, very unfavourable, so,

497
00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:23.280
people,

498
00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:24.280
always very,

499
00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:25.280
very important,

500
00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:26.280
that the date is correct.

501
00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:27.280
Now,

502
00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:28.280
as you see on this chart,

503
00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:30.280
the LSR drawn in red

504
00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.280
are not very widespread.

505
00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:34.280
They're not very active.

506
00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:35.280
By the way,

507
00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:36.280
in our area,

508
00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:38.280
in the Alpstein,

509
00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:39.280
it isn't active either,

510
00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:40.280
so it doesn't mean

511
00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:41.280
they're always active,

512
00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:43.280
just because they're on the glider chart.

513
00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:44.280
These are just those

514
00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:45.280
that are used very often,

515
00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:46.280
and therefore,

516
00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:47.280
are permanently on the chart.

517
00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:48.280
they are.

518
00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:49.280
But on the day itself,

519
00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:50.280
you can always quickly

520
00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:51.280
check DABS,

521
00:24:51.280 --> 00:24:52.280
I've got here,

522
00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:53.280
as an example,

523
00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:55.280
the D12 exactly,

524
00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:56.280
near Einsiedeln,

525
00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:57.280
nearby,

526
00:24:57.280 --> 00:24:58.280
there's,

527
00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:00.280
very little info about it above,

528
00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:01.280
and below it,

529
00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:02.280
in the legend,

530
00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:03.790
we then see,

531
00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:05.890
when,

532
00:25:05.890 --> 00:25:06.890
and how high,

533
00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:07.890
that,

534
00:25:07.890 --> 00:25:08.890
therefore,

535
00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:09.890
is closed,

536
00:25:09.890 --> 00:25:10.890
or,

537
00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:11.890
as a danger area

538
00:25:11.890 --> 00:25:12.890
is declared,

539
00:25:12.890 --> 00:25:13.890
and also,

540
00:25:13.890 --> 00:25:14.890
when,

541
00:25:14.890 --> 00:25:15.890
from when,

542
00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:16.890
it's done.

543
00:25:16.890 --> 00:25:17.890
I also recommend

544
00:25:17.890 --> 00:25:18.890
looking,

545
00:25:18.890 --> 00:25:19.890
just every once in a while,

546
00:25:19.890 --> 00:25:20.890
also when you,

547
00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:21.890
perhaps aren't out flying

548
00:25:21.890 --> 00:25:22.890
and are at the office,

549
00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:23.890
during the day,

550
00:25:23.890 --> 00:25:24.890
have a look,

551
00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:25.890
briefly,

552
00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:26.890
I find it interesting,

553
00:25:26.890 --> 00:25:27.890
you discover all sorts of things,

554
00:25:27.890 --> 00:25:31.180
good.

555
00:25:31.180 --> 00:25:32.180
It's just not much,

556
00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:34.180
(unclear),

557
00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:36.180
(unclear)

558
00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:37.180
Well,

559
00:25:37.180 --> 00:25:55.180
of course it is,

560
00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:57.180
(unclear)

561
00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:36.740
and here you can see what it looks like.

562
00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:39.870
On the glider chart it's quite a tricky one.

563
00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:41.870
There we said, almost not,

564
00:26:41.870 --> 00:26:44.870
but stupidly it's a bit fiddly.

565
00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:46.870
That's why the topic, the topic

566
00:26:46.870 --> 00:26:48.870
needs to be handled a bit differently than others.

567
00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:55.560
Now we've talked an extreme amount about restrictions,

568
00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:57.560
about dangers, about limitations.

569
00:26:57.560 --> 00:27:03.560
Now I'll say a bit on the positive side about the glider chart,

570
00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:06.560
about an advantage for us paraglider pilots.

571
00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:09.560
And those are the LSR for Gliders.

572
00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:11.560
These are the glider zones.

573
00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:13.560
They're drawn in green.

574
00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:14.560
It's also an LSR,

575
00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:16.560
but it isn't restricted for us.

576
00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:20.560
It's restricted for instrument-flight aircraft

577
00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:23.560
or instrument flight in aircraft,

578
00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:26.560
and that's why it's an advantage for us,

579
00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:28.560
because we can fly closer to clouds there.

580
00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.560
We'll come to the cloud clearances in a moment.

581
00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:32.560
And what that means exactly,

582
00:27:32.560 --> 00:27:38.560
the LSRs are active from 1 March to 31 October.

583
00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:41.560
But watch out for the time window.

584
00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:43.560
It doesn't apply if, for example,

585
00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:46.560
you have a really good thermal day in February

586
00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:48.560
and you're flying thermals.

587
00:27:48.560 --> 00:27:50.560
But you might not even be aware

588
00:27:50.560 --> 00:27:52.560
that the glider zones aren't active.

589
00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:56.560
So watch out, they only start on 1 March.

590
00:27:56.560 --> 00:27:59.560
And also for exams, for theory exams.

591
00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:01.560
But also for theory exams,

592
00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:03.560
also for practical exams.

593
00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:05.560
If you do the exam in winter,

594
00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:07.560
it could be that the examiner perhaps

595
00:28:07.560 --> 00:28:09.560
asks a slightly tricky question

596
00:28:09.560 --> 00:28:11.560
about the glider zones,

597
00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:13.560
which then might not be active.

598
00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:15.560
They look like this,

599
00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:17.560
framed in green,

600
00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:20.560
and there too we have lower and upper limits

601
00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:24.000
on the glider chart.

602
00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
And once we're talking about LSRs,

603
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
we can necessarily move

604
00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
to the topic of cloud clearances.

605
00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.450
Cloud clearances are regulated such

606
00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:37.450
that up to 300 m above ground

607
00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:39.450
no cloud clearance is required.

608
00:28:39.450 --> 00:28:42.450
We have to be outside the clouds at all times

609
00:28:42.450 --> 00:28:44.450
and also able to make a turn-around.

610
00:28:44.450 --> 00:28:47.450
So we can't fly from the valley into the clouds.

611
00:28:47.450 --> 00:28:49.450
Or be half inside,

612
00:28:49.450 --> 00:28:51.450
but we always have to be able to turn around.

613
00:28:51.450 --> 00:28:53.450
That's very important.

614
00:28:53.450 --> 00:28:56.450
Horizontal visibility must be half a kilometre,

615
00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:58.450
and you must always have ground in sight.

616
00:28:58.450 --> 00:29:01.450
This rule applies up to 300 m.

617
00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:03.450
That's a bit unusual.

618
00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:05.450
It isn't simply said,

619
00:29:05.450 --> 00:29:07.450
it applies in airspace G,

620
00:29:07.450 --> 00:29:09.450
but only the lower half of G.

621
00:29:09.450 --> 00:29:12.450
It's only 300 m and not 600 m,

622
00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:14.450
where the limit is drawn.

623
00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:16.450
We have to think about that too.

624
00:29:16.450 --> 00:29:18.450
Anything above 300 m,

625
00:29:18.450 --> 00:29:21.450
you have to keep fairly large cloud clearances.

626
00:29:21.450 --> 00:29:25.450
Vertically it's 300 m and horizontally

627
00:29:25.450 --> 00:29:28.450
1500 m clearance from clouds.

628
00:29:28.450 --> 00:29:32.610
In terms of visibility, it's not just half a kilometre,

629
00:29:32.610 --> 00:29:35.610
but goes up to 5 km,

630
00:29:35.610 --> 00:29:37.610
respectively 8 km,

631
00:29:37.610 --> 00:29:40.610
as soon as you fly above 3050.

632
00:29:40.610 --> 00:29:42.610
And it has to do with the speed

633
00:29:42.610 --> 00:29:44.610
of the aircraft,

634
00:29:44.610 --> 00:29:47.610
because higher up, faster speeds are flown

635
00:29:47.610 --> 00:29:49.610
and of course you need more time

636
00:29:49.610 --> 00:29:51.610
to react and to be able to avoid.

637
00:29:51.610 --> 00:29:54.610
And aircraft that fly there in the clouds,

638
00:29:54.610 --> 00:29:56.610
and well, when they pop out of the clouds,

639
00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:59.610
if there were only 500 m clearance to the clouds,

640
00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:00.610
then of course

641
00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:02.610
it could get tight in some circumstances.

642
00:30:02.610 --> 00:30:04.610
That's why we have higher,

643
00:30:04.610 --> 00:30:08.340
larger cloud clearances.

644
00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:09.340
In addition,

645
00:30:09.340 --> 00:30:11.340
in the special case,

646
00:30:11.340 --> 00:30:12.340
of glider zones,

647
00:30:12.340 --> 00:30:14.590
all those LSR for Gliders,

648
00:30:14.590 --> 00:30:16.590
it looks a bit different.

649
00:30:16.590 --> 00:30:18.590
In these zones we have

650
00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:20.590
a reduced cloud clearance,

651
00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:22.590
namely 50 m vertical

652
00:30:22.590 --> 00:30:24.590
and 100 m horizontal,

653
00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:26.590
there on the right side

654
00:30:26.590 --> 00:30:28.590
again the lower limit

655
00:30:28.590 --> 00:30:29.590
and the upper limit

656
00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:31.590
of the zone

657
00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:33.590
or of the airspace.

658
00:30:33.590 --> 00:30:35.590
And it's important here

659
00:30:35.590 --> 00:30:38.590
that you don't just give up

660
00:30:38.590 --> 00:30:39.590
or think

661
00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:43.590
that now at 2450 you're always in a super thermal

662
00:30:43.590 --> 00:30:45.590
that you have to fly out

663
00:30:45.590 --> 00:30:47.590
and abandon.

664
00:30:47.590 --> 00:30:48.590
And there, you can definitely,

665
00:30:48.590 --> 00:30:50.590
climb out higher.

666
00:30:50.590 --> 00:30:51.590
The only thing

667
00:30:51.590 --> 00:30:52.590
that changes again,

668
00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:53.590
once you're above,

669
00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:54.590
are the cloud clearances.

670
00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:56.590
So as soon as you're up,

671
00:30:56.590 --> 00:30:58.590
for example at 2.5 km,

672
00:30:58.590 --> 00:31:01.910
the big cloud clearances apply again.

673
00:31:01.910 --> 00:31:03.910
Here it's also important to know,

674
00:31:03.910 --> 00:31:04.910
and sometimes

675
00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:06.910
comes up in theory-exam questions,

676
00:31:06.910 --> 00:31:08.910
so they're set up,

677
00:31:08.910 --> 00:31:10.910
so that you might mistakenly

678
00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:11.910
assume,

679
00:31:11.910 --> 00:31:12.910
you can only go up to 2450.

680
00:31:12.910 --> 00:31:14.910
But that doesn't apply to flying,

681
00:31:14.910 --> 00:31:16.910
rather it only applies to the cloud clearances

682
00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:19.740
that you have to maintain.

683
00:31:19.740 --> 00:31:21.740
Because many of these LSRs

684
00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:23.740
don't have any extras.

685
00:31:23.740 --> 00:31:24.740
And just have heights,

686
00:31:24.740 --> 00:31:26.740
sometimes in standard atmosphere,

687
00:31:26.740 --> 00:31:28.740
sometimes above sea level.

688
00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:31.740
And some have an addition

689
00:31:31.740 --> 00:31:32.740
of MON.

690
00:31:32.740 --> 00:31:33.740
MON means,

691
00:31:33.740 --> 00:31:35.740
it's only active

692
00:31:35.740 --> 00:31:36.740
when the military

693
00:31:36.740 --> 00:31:38.740
is off,

694
00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:40.740
so when the military isn't active.

695
00:31:40.740 --> 00:31:43.740
MON is always active

696
00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:46.740
when the military isn't in.

697
00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:48.740
With MON, the difference is,

698
00:31:48.740 --> 00:31:50.740
if that's the case,

699
00:31:50.740 --> 00:31:52.740
it can be,

700
00:31:52.740 --> 00:31:54.740
that it then gets cleared straight away.

701
00:31:54.740 --> 00:31:56.740
And then we have to make a request.

702
00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:58.740
So if the military is active,

703
00:31:58.740 --> 00:31:59.740
and MON is shown,

704
00:31:59.740 --> 00:32:00.740
you can make a request.

705
00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:02.740
Maybe they'll release the airspace,

706
00:32:02.740 --> 00:32:03.740
because the military

707
00:32:03.740 --> 00:32:05.740
perhaps isn't at that location at all

708
00:32:05.740 --> 00:32:07.740
or isn't using the airspace at all,

709
00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:08.740
at that point in time.

710
00:32:08.740 --> 00:32:09.740
Exactly.

711
00:32:09.740 --> 00:32:13.980
So, now we've heard a whole,

712
00:32:13.980 --> 00:32:15.980
whole lot of theory.

713
00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:16.980
I hope

714
00:32:16.980 --> 00:32:18.980
I haven't worn you out.

715
00:32:18.980 --> 00:32:20.980
Now we're getting to a theory question,

716
00:32:20.980 --> 00:32:23.980
as a kind of warm-up for the theory exam,

717
00:32:23.980 --> 00:32:26.980
and of course also for flying.

718
00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:28.980
When at some point we're standing on a launch site,

719
00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:29.980
and we want to know,

720
00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:31.980
okay, how high can I fly there,

721
00:32:31.980 --> 00:32:33.980
what cloud clearances do I have to keep,

722
00:32:33.980 --> 00:32:34.980
how far do I have to see?

723
00:32:34.980 --> 00:32:36.980
And am I even legal here,

724
00:32:36.980 --> 00:32:39.980
or should I rather not launch.

725
00:32:39.980 --> 00:32:42.850
Basically I always ask myself

726
00:32:42.850 --> 00:32:44.850
five questions

727
00:32:44.850 --> 00:32:46.850
when I'm at any given spot.

728
00:32:46.850 --> 00:32:48.850
First, what time of year is it,

729
00:32:48.850 --> 00:32:50.850
because of the glider zones.

730
00:32:50.850 --> 00:32:53.850
So am I between March and October,

731
00:32:53.850 --> 00:32:54.850
or am I in winter,

732
00:32:54.850 --> 00:32:56.850
because that influences my cloud clearances

733
00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:58.850
in a given case,

734
00:32:58.850 --> 00:33:01.850
within a glider zone.

735
00:33:01.850 --> 00:33:03.850
The second is the weekday

736
00:33:03.850 --> 00:33:05.850
and time of day, because of the military.

737
00:33:05.850 --> 00:33:08.850
To know how high I can climb,

738
00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:10.850
if it's running really well today.

739
00:33:10.850 --> 00:33:11.850
Then I have to know,

740
00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:12.850
am I north or south

741
00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:14.850
of the dividing line,

742
00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:16.850
am I in the Mittelland or am I in the Alps.

743
00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:19.230
The altitude I'm at right now,

744
00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:21.230
is very important to know,

745
00:33:21.230 --> 00:33:22.230
and also the location.

746
00:33:22.230 --> 00:33:23.230
So am I,

747
00:33:23.230 --> 00:33:25.230
perhaps already somewhere in the radius,

748
00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:27.230
of a helipad

749
00:33:27.230 --> 00:33:30.230
or am I in some kind of special zone.

750
00:33:30.230 --> 00:33:32.230
And that's very important.

751
00:33:32.230 --> 00:33:34.230
If you can answer these five questions

752
00:33:34.230 --> 00:33:35.230
for yourselves,

753
00:33:35.230 --> 00:33:36.230
then we'll get

754
00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:39.230
to the solution relatively quickly.

755
00:33:39.230 --> 00:33:42.460
Maybe you can pause quickly

756
00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:44.460
and not move on to the next slide yet

757
00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:46.460
and think through the exercise yourself.

758
00:33:46.460 --> 00:33:48.460
And on the next slide

759
00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:53.820
the explanation will come.

760
00:33:53.820 --> 00:33:54.820
Yes, as you see,

761
00:33:54.820 --> 00:33:56.820
it's standard pressure.

762
00:33:56.820 --> 00:33:58.820
There's a maximum,

763
00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:00.820
altitude of 3050,

764
00:34:00.820 --> 00:34:03.820
because we're north of the line.

765
00:34:03.820 --> 00:34:04.820
It's a bit tricky here.

766
00:34:04.820 --> 00:34:05.820
It really,

767
00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:07.820
goes right up to the boundary at Montreux,

768
00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:08.820
but slightly,

769
00:34:08.820 --> 00:34:10.820
or slightly to the left of it,

770
00:34:10.820 --> 00:34:11.820
so that means,

771
00:34:11.820 --> 00:34:12.820
we're in the Mittelland.

772
00:34:12.820 --> 00:34:13.820
That means,

773
00:34:13.820 --> 00:34:15.820
the answer with 4550

774
00:34:15.820 --> 00:34:17.820
we can actually already cross off.

775
00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:19.820
And quite often you get there

776
00:34:19.820 --> 00:34:21.820
by what the theory exam also requires,

777
00:34:21.820 --> 00:34:24.820
namely using process of elimination to find the correct answer.

778
00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:26.820
Flying forbidden,

779
00:34:26.820 --> 00:34:28.820
as you see here, there's no reason,

780
00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:29.820
we don't have an airfield,

781
00:34:29.820 --> 00:34:31.820
no helipad nearby,

782
00:34:31.820 --> 00:34:33.820
we're not in a red danger zone

783
00:34:33.820 --> 00:34:36.820
or whatever else might be drawn there.

784
00:34:36.820 --> 00:34:40.170
Everything looks fine for flying.

785
00:34:40.170 --> 00:34:44.170
Altitude is the same for B and for C.

786
00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:46.170
Now we have to figure out,

787
00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:48.170
how it is with cloud clearances.

788
00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:51.170
We're at 2700 metres up.

789
00:34:51.170 --> 00:34:52.170
That means,

790
00:34:52.170 --> 00:34:54.170
the visibility is 5 kilometres.

791
00:34:54.170 --> 00:34:55.170
You can see that there.

792
00:34:55.170 --> 00:34:57.170
Both say 5 kilometres.

793
00:34:57.170 --> 00:34:59.170
Because we're still under the three,

794
00:34:59.170 --> 00:35:01.170
3050.

795
00:35:01.170 --> 00:35:03.170
Or rather,

796
00:35:03.170 --> 00:35:04.170
we don't need higher,

797
00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:05.170
because we're in the Mittelland.

798
00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:07.520
As for cloud clearances,

799
00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:09.520
though, whether it's enough or fine,

800
00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:10.520
we have to think,

801
00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:13.520
are we in a glider zone or not.

802
00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:15.520
And here it's a bit sneaky.

803
00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:16.520
You might think,

804
00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:17.520
we're in one.

805
00:35:17.520 --> 00:35:18.520
But if you read

806
00:35:18.520 --> 00:35:19.520
below,

807
00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:21.520
at LSR 21 exactly,

808
00:35:21.520 --> 00:35:24.520
the LSR for Gliders

809
00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:27.520
only goes up to 2450 metres.

810
00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:31.520
But we're already in the air at 2700.

811
00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:32.520
That means,

812
00:35:32.520 --> 00:35:33.520
we're above it.

813
00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:34.520
We're allowed to fly.

814
00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:35.520
It's not forbidden.

815
00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:37.520
But unfortunately we have to

816
00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:38.520
maintain the big cloud clearances.

817
00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:41.520
